🧡Chicken Samsy: OMG this was my absolute favorite of the night! The handmade baked pastry was so crispy and filled with a juicy meat and onion filling! It kind of reminds me of Vietnamese pate chaud. I wanted to eat 10 of these 😂  🧡Manty & Oromo: Manty was the fried dumplings with a similar filling as the Samsy and was super delicious 😋 the Oromo was surprisingly really tasty! It’s all vegan and filled with potatoes. I loved dipping it in their red sauce!  🧡Chicken and beef skewers: these were decent and I liked the chicken more than the beef! I’ve had more flavorful beef skewers at other places haha  🧡Plov: amazing!! The rice was so flavorful and the lamb on the top wasn’t too gamey! I usually don’t like lamb but this tasted good ❤️  🧡Honey cake: omg I’ve been wanting to try this cake forever! I really like how it wasn’t too sweet yet moist! Perfect with tea or coffee 😋  🧡Walnut cake: my bf’s fave! 😆 it was a rich cake filled with lots of walnuts and caramel!  Overall, they really impressed me with the strong flavors and high execution of the dishes! I can see why they have 3 locations: Chicago, Naperville, and Glenview. Definitely want to try out more of their food again! 🤩

What a find! We discovered this restaurant by accident and loved the food, ambience, and service. Delicious central Asian cuisine. Two of us got the vegetarian combo of Oromo (steamed pie with potatoes, onions, cabbage, and carrots), Plov (a rice dish) , Vareniki (dumplings stuffed with mashed potatoes), and Pelmeni (dumplings stuffed with spinach. Delicious! Our third order was the traditional assortment of Manty (dumplings stuffed with chopped beef and onions), Oromo, Plov (rice seasoned with beef, lamb, and vegetable broth), Pelmeni (dumplings stuffed with beef), Lagman (stewed beef and vegetables served with hand pulled noodles), and Kotlety (turkey and beef patties). Also wonderful. The homemade Naan was warm and tasty. We had honey cake for dessert (lovely, light and not too sweet) and it was the perfect end to a great meal. Highly recommended. We'll be back!

Jibek Jolu offers a rare Kyrgyzstani menu to Chicago. It is a Central Asian mix of cuisines from Russia, Turkey, China, India, Afghanistan, and more. The word "flavor" barely scratches the surface of how amazing their food is. Each dish is unique and seemingly more tasty than the last.  Their food comes from Central Asia. As an ignorant American sauntering in during my first visit I imagined the food to be like a spin on Chinese or something like that. That is totally wrong. The food is actually more similar to what my Grandma from Poland used to make. Lots of dumplings, potato, and huge meat dishes. However, it is very unique and you just won't understand until you try it.  It is easy to tell that their food is all homemade and prepared fresh. If you're looking microwaved, prepackaged frozen meals you'll have to move on. Nothing but food made in house. Their kitchen is pretty easy to see into and you'll quickly notice many chefs cooking.  I highly recommend the pelmeni and manty. These are steamed dumplings filled with some of the most flavorful meat I've ever had. Every time I go there I've also had the Jibek Jolu special which is like a cucumber and meat stir fry but has such a unique flavor unlike traditional Chinese stir fry dishes.  Many friends and coworkers have tried this place because of my recommendation and absolutely love it! Several of them were reluctant to try these things due to the strange names and descriptions. They were all won over by the flavor.  The place feels cozy inside and the staff is super friendly. They are also byob which is a cool way to save money on your dinner.  Many of their dishes are designed to be shared so you can try many things. To feel full expect to spend around $25 per person for your visit. This is also a great place to get take out. HIGHLY RECOMMEND!

This used to be an incredible place. Four walls, blank and unfinished, creaky tables and delicious, warm, Central Asian Granny's Kitchen-type food. But as the walls got more decorated, as the volume of the loud, annoying Russian pop was turned down, the quality of the food - and the service - took a dive. Cold food, clearly microwaved pastries, routinely over charging, and forgetting orders is commonplace now. It's a very sad situation, but it doesn't need to be a permanent one. Here's to hoping they up their game at this fantastic halal joint and prove that a Kyrgyz place isn't  too niche for the this end of the North Side.
